# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carnism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carnism/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:carnism/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:carnism/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:carnism/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:carnism/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:carnism/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:carnism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:carnism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:carnism/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:carnism/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:carnism/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:carnism/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
[src:carnism/carnism] Central to the ideology is the acceptance of meat-eating as "natural", "normal", "necessary", and (sometimes) "nice", known as the "Four Ns".
[src:carnism/carnism] An important feature of carnism is the classification of only particular species of animal as food, and the acceptance of practices toward those animals that would be rejected as unacceptable cruelty if applied to other species.
[src:carnism/carnism] This classification is culturally relative, so that, for example, dogs are eaten by some people in Korea but may be pets in the West, while cows are eaten in the West but protected in much of India.
[src:carnism/carnism] Analyzing the history of vegetarianism and opposition to it from ancient Greece to the present day, literary scholar Renan Larue found certain commonalities in what he described as carnist arguments.
[src:carnism/carnism] According to him, carnists typically held that vegetarianism is a ludicrous idea unworthy of attention, that mankind is invested with dominion over animals by divine authority, and that abstaining from violence against animals would pose a threat to humans.
[src:carnism/carnism] In the 1970s, traditional views on the moral standing of animals were challenged by animal rights advocates, including psychologist Richard Ryder, who in 1971 introduced the notion of speciesism.
[src:carnism/carnism] This is defined as the assignment of value and rights to individuals solely on the basis of their species membership.
[src:carnism/carnism] In 2001, psychologist and animal rights advocate Melanie Joy coined the term *carnism* for a form of speciesism that she argues underpins killing animals for meat.
[src:carnism/carnism] Sandra Mahlke argues that carnism is the "central crux of speciesism" because the eating of meat motivates ideological justification for other forms of animal exploitation.
[src:carnism/carnism] Abolitionist Gary Francione argues against this that carnism is not a hidden ideology, but a conscious choice; in his view some animals are viewed as food and others family because humans regard non-humans as property, and they may value that property as they please.
[src:carnism/carnism] A central aspect of carnism is that animals are categorized as edible, inedible, pets, vermin, predators, or entertainment animals, according to people's schemata – mental classifications that determine, and are determined by, our beliefs and desires.
[src:carnism/carnism] There is cultural variability regarding which animals count as food: Dogs are eaten in China and South Korea, but elsewhere are not viewed as food, either because they are loved, or, as in the Middle East and parts of India, regarded as unclean.
[src:carnism/carnism] Cows are eaten in the West but revered in much of India.
[src:carnism/carnism] Pigs are rejected by Muslims and Jews but widely regarded by other groups as edible.
[src:carnism/carnism] Joy and other psychologists argue that these taxonomies determine how the animals within them are treated, influence subjective perceptions of their sentience and intelligence, and reduce or increase empathy and moral concern for them.
[src:carnism/carnism] Jeff Mannes writes that carnism is rooted in a paradox between most people's values and actions: they oppose harming animals, and yet eat them.
[src:carnism/carnism] He argues that this conflict leads to cognitive dissonance, which people attempt to attenuate through psychic numbing.
[src:carnism/carnism] The apparent conflict between caring about animals and embracing non-vegetarian diets has been termed the "meat paradox".
[src:carnism/carnism] There is experimental evidence supporting the idea that the meat paradox induces cognitive dissonance in Westerners.
[src:carnism/carnism] Westerners are more willing to eat animals which they regard as having lesser mental capacities and moral standing, and conversely, to attribute lesser mental faculties and moral standing to animals which are eaten.
[src:carnism/carnism] Furthermore, the relationship is causative: the categorization of animals as food or not affects people's perception of their mental characteristics, and the act of eating meat itself causes people to attribute diminished mental capacity to animals.
[src:carnism/carnism] For example, in one study people rated an unfamiliar exotic animal as less intelligent if they were told native people hunted it, and in another they regarded cows as less intelligent after eating beef jerky.
[src:carnism/carnism] Avoiding consideration of the provenance of meat is another strategy.
[src:carnism/carnism] Joy argues that this is why meat is rarely served with the animal's head or other intact body parts.
[src:carnism/carnism] Joy introduced the idea of the "Three Ns of Justification", writing that meat-eaters regard meat consumption as "normal, natural, and necessary".
[src:carnism/carnism] She argues that the "Three Ns" have been invoked to justify other ideologies, including slavery and denying women the right to vote, and are widely recognized as problematic only after the ideology they support has been dismantled.
[src:carnism/carnism] The argument holds that people are conditioned to believe that humans evolved to eat meat, that it is expected of them, and that they need it to survive or be strong.
[src:carnism/carnism] These beliefs are said to be reinforced by various institutions, including religion, family, and the media.
[src:carnism/carnism] Although scientists have shown that humans can get enough protein in their diets without eating meat, the belief that meat is required persists.
[src:carnism/carnism] Moreover, a 2022 study published in *PNAS* calls into question the impact of meat consumption on shaping the evolution of the human species.
[src:carnism/carnism] Building on Joy's work, psychologists conducted a series of studies in the United States and Australia, published in 2015, that found the great majority of meat-eaters' stated justifications for consuming meat were based on the "Four Ns" – "natural, normal, necessary, and nice".
[src:carnism/carnism] The arguments were that humans are omnivores (*natural*), that most people eat meat (*normal*), that vegetarian diets are lacking in nutrients (*necessary*), and that meat tastes good (*nice*).
[src:carnism/carnism] Meat-eaters who endorsed these arguments more strongly reported less guilt about their dietary habits.
[src:carnism/carnism] They tended to objectify animals, have less moral concern for them and attribute less consciousness to them.
[src:carnism/carnism] They were also more supportive of social inequality and hierarchical ideologies, and less proud of their consumer choices.
[src:carnism/carnism] An illustration of dissonance reduction is the prominence given to "saved from slaughter" stories, in which the media focus on one animal that evaded slaughter, while ignoring the millions that did not.
[src:carnism/carnism] Joy wrote that this dichotomy is characteristic of carnism.
[src:carnism/carnism] Animals at the center of these narratives include Wilbur in *Charlotte's Web* (1952); the eponymous and fictional star of *Babe* (1995); Christopher Hogwood in Sy Montgomery's *The Good, Good Pig* (2006); the Tamworth Two; Emily the Cow and Cincinnati Freedom.
[src:carnism/carnism] The American National Thanksgiving Turkey Presentation is cited as another example.
[src:carnism/carnism] A 2012 study found that most media reporting on it celebrated the poultry industry while marginalizing the link between living animals and meat.
[src:carnism/carnism] Opinion pieces in *The Huffington Post*, *The Statesman*, and *The Drum* praised the idea, saying the term made it easier to discuss, and challenge, the practices of animal exploitation.
[src:carnism/carnism] An article in the beef industry outlet *Drovers Cattle Network* criticized the use of the term, saying it implied that eating animal foods was a "psychological sickness".
